1
00:00:00,540 --> 00:00:01,920
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,600 --> 00:00:06,460
Continuing work on building the lab power supply.

3
00:00:06,980 --> 00:00:10,640
Here in front of you is part of its schematic.

4
00:00:11,300 --> 00:00:16,180
What we've already managed to do, so to speak, in metal.

5
00:00:16,800 --> 00:00:20,800
And this part we'll test today.

6
00:00:21,800 --> 00:00:24,140
A quick look at the schematic.

7
00:00:24,140 --> 00:00:30,500
The master generator is built on a UC3825N chip.

8
00:00:31,020 --> 00:00:38,260
The PWM controller is built on it too, with current and voltage feedback.

9
00:00:38,680 --> 00:00:45,500
Right now you can see the current feedback isn't yet added.

10
00:00:46,080 --> 00:00:48,400
So we'll test the system without it.

11
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:54,880
Current feedback goes to pin 9 through a 1 kΩ resistor.

12
00:00:55,120 --> 00:01:06,740
For the chip to start in this configuration, pin 9 through this resistor needs to be tied to the common — to minus power.

13
00:01:08,040 --> 00:01:16,180
You can also see the controller outputs come from pin 14 and pin 11.

14
00:01:16,180 --> 00:01:24,880
On the schematic I marked pin 14 as "1" and pin 11 as "2" in a circle.

15
00:01:25,660 --> 00:01:27,860
And now we can trace the control.

16
00:01:28,100 --> 00:01:31,340
"1" goes to this opto-driver.

17
00:01:31,480 --> 00:01:35,460
And you also see "1" goes to a driver diagonally.

18
00:01:36,140 --> 00:01:38,160
The switches work this way too.

19
00:01:38,380 --> 00:01:40,740
That is, the switches work crosswise.

20
00:01:41,120 --> 00:01:44,500
One pair and the second pair.

21
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:53,900
This way we create bipolar current pulses through the primary winding of the pulse transformer.

22
00:01:54,580 --> 00:02:00,500
You can also see separate power for each of the four drivers.

23
00:02:00,780 --> 00:02:03,180
Marked plus-minus on the schematic.

24
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:07,900
And 16 V is supplied at these points.

25
00:02:08,460 --> 00:02:10,960
This power is galvanically isolated.

26
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:17,160
And the same power is supplied separately to the PWM controller itself.

27
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:24,560
I supplied it from a DC-DC converter with 5 outputs.

28
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:27,340
The schematic can be found on my channel.

29
00:02:27,640 --> 00:02:31,080
And a video on building it.

30
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:38,260
The optical feedback for us will also be by voltage.

31
00:02:38,260 --> 00:02:41,700
Here you can see a PC817 optocoupler.

32
00:02:43,100 --> 00:02:49,620
I routed its output to pin 1.

33
00:02:49,740 --> 00:02:56,620
And it gets power from pin 16 through a 1 kΩ current-limiting resistor.

34
00:02:57,440 --> 00:03:09,980
This optocoupler is planned for use as a sensor for the limit voltage of the power supply — namely 1000 V.

35
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:20,540
At 1000 V at the output, the converter should enter limiting mode to maintain this potential.

36
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:30,680
Up to 1000 V, voltage regulation will be done with this trim pot variable resistor.

37
00:03:30,680 --> 00:03:41,580
You can also see I picked the values of the resistors in series with the variable resistor.

38
00:03:41,800 --> 00:03:52,740
So that regulation is smooth across the entire travel of the variable resistor.

39
00:03:52,920 --> 00:03:55,680
Which is very convenient for regulation.

40
00:03:55,680 --> 00:04:09,200
I also picked them so that if the slider is at the extreme left position, the chip stops generation and the power supply goes to standby mode.

41
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:20,220
You can see in the schematic that the PWM controller is powered from the 16 V potential supplied to pin 15 of the chip.

42
00:04:21,110 --> 00:04:28,860
Pin 13 is powered with 12 V, which comes from an L7812 regulator.

43
00:04:29,580 --> 00:04:39,300
That's done to apply 12 V to the input LEDs of the opto-drivers.

44
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:42,320
Limit voltage.

45
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:47,540
12 V is plenty for these drivers and they work great.

46
00:04:47,540 --> 00:05:07,740
I applied this potential through a 470 Ω current-limiting resistor and also a 1 kΩ resistor in parallel with the LED in the driver, which excludes false triggering of the opto-driver in this

47
00:05:07,740 --> 00:05:08,760
system.

48
00:05:08,760 --> 00:05:18,760
Now I'll show how it looks in metal and then move to testing and tuning the block.

49
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:21,120
This is the block in assembly.

50
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:24,260
What can you see here?

51
00:05:24,900 --> 00:05:35,240
I made a bus that supplies power and connects with the rest of the device's controls.

52
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:39,340
This is a separable unit.

53
00:05:40,140 --> 00:05:46,360
Further — DC-DC converter with 5 galvanically isolated outputs.

54
00:05:47,040 --> 00:05:51,200
4 HCPL3120 opto-drivers.

55
00:05:51,780 --> 00:05:56,540
The PWM controller chip itself — UC3825N.

56
00:05:56,800 --> 00:05:59,900
This is our L7812 regulator.

57
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:07,160
Of the main support components of the drivers.

58
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:10,520
These are resistor chains.

59
00:06:11,460 --> 00:06:15,420
And here visible are 1-watt resistors.

60
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:21,340
These chains go to the FET gate.

61
00:06:22,060 --> 00:06:27,920
You can also see bundles of 15 V counter-connected zeners here.

62
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:32,300
These parts are in parallel with the transistor leads.

63
00:06:33,420 --> 00:06:43,600
On the schematic you can see I set one of the current-limiting resistor values.

64
00:06:43,760 --> 00:06:46,560
This is 4.7 Ω on the gate.

65
00:06:47,020 --> 00:06:49,060
The second value isn't marked yet.

66
00:06:50,120 --> 00:06:56,020
By default I have the same 4.7 Ω resistor connected on the board.

67
00:06:56,020 --> 00:07:03,000
In practice I'll pick, and if needed the value of this resistor will be reduced.

68
00:07:03,740 --> 00:07:09,940
For higher-quality FET gate opening on the leading edge.

69
00:07:10,160 --> 00:07:11,740
But again, only if needed.

70
00:07:12,320 --> 00:07:21,100
This resistor is the part responsible for controlling the voltage potential.

71
00:07:24,500 --> 00:07:31,420
Nothing else here to dwell on in detail.

72
00:07:32,500 --> 00:07:35,200
The power pulse transformer is connected.

73
00:07:38,020 --> 00:07:47,280
I decided to make the primary winding with insulated wire — multi-strand pure copper.

74
00:07:48,020 --> 00:07:49,940
In thermally stable insulation.

75
00:07:50,760 --> 00:07:57,960
7 turns, which corresponds to about 14 V at a fully charged battery.

76
00:07:58,100 --> 00:08:02,700
2 V per turn of primary winding.

77
00:08:03,060 --> 00:08:04,920
So, all ready for testing.

78
00:08:05,080 --> 00:08:10,460
Now we need to see how the optical drivers are controlled.

79
00:08:11,370 --> 00:08:19,300
For this we'll look at the initial work of the PWM controller at these points.

80
00:08:19,660 --> 00:08:21,140
Point 1 and point 2.

81
00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:33,280
Our control pulses are supplied in antiphase, and at their maximum duration the PWM controller leaves a pause between them — so-called dead time.

82
00:08:35,140 --> 00:08:38,800
I connected the oscilloscope probes at these points.

83
00:08:38,800 --> 00:08:43,260
Now I apply power to the DC-DC converter.

84
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:48,080
Now you'll hear the working core sound.

85
00:08:48,840 --> 00:08:56,680
And as the pulse duration changes, the DC-DC converter will adapt to consumption and the tonality of this sound will change.

86
00:08:57,880 --> 00:08:59,340
I applied power.

87
00:09:00,740 --> 00:09:03,120
DC-DC converter started.

88
00:09:04,100 --> 00:09:08,200
You see the oscillogram changed slightly.

89
00:09:08,200 --> 00:09:18,560
And now I move the variable resistor slider out of the extreme position where the PWM controller doesn't work.

90
00:09:19,200 --> 00:09:20,600
Smoothly adding.

91
00:09:22,560 --> 00:09:25,980
You see a minimum pulse appeared.

92
00:09:26,740 --> 00:09:32,020
And you can hear the DC-DC converter changed tonality.

93
00:09:32,620 --> 00:09:34,400
Such is its feature.

94
00:09:34,960 --> 00:09:41,380
We're interested in how smoothly the control pulse duration changes.

95
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:46,480
Bringing to the limit.

96
00:09:47,020 --> 00:09:51,340
End of the resistor slider.

97
00:09:52,480 --> 00:09:57,840
And now observe whether there's a pause between control pulses.

98
00:09:57,840 --> 00:10:03,280
Yes, the pause is actually present in time.

99
00:10:05,160 --> 00:10:06,980
Now let's see what it is.

100
00:10:08,740 --> 00:10:12,700
Set the sweep to 100 ns per cell.

101
00:10:13,940 --> 00:10:22,200
And it turns out 100, 200, 300, 400 ns is the pause on this PWM controller.

102
00:10:23,200 --> 00:10:37,920
Since we've confirmed everything works, we can now look at how the optical driver behaves under load on the FET gate.

103
00:10:38,460 --> 00:10:49,160
For this I'll switch the blue oscilloscope channel to the output of the optical driver.

104
00:10:49,160 --> 00:10:53,800
Place it directly on the FET gate.

105
00:10:58,040 --> 00:11:03,900
And here we can already observe its real work under load.

106
00:11:06,920 --> 00:11:16,080
First let's look at how duration changes.

107
00:11:19,990 --> 00:11:22,370
Control channel — yellow.

108
00:11:26,640 --> 00:11:29,860
The optical driver works properly.

109
00:11:30,520 --> 00:11:37,580
Now we can observe the switch-opening edge.

110
00:11:39,140 --> 00:11:45,540
We'll need to look at the edge of the blue oscilloscope channel.

111
00:11:46,540 --> 00:11:50,880
Also at 100 ns per cell.

112
00:11:53,600 --> 00:12:01,180
These small interferences you can see — this is DC-DC converter operation.

113
00:12:01,440 --> 00:12:06,540
But this is absolutely not critical and doesn't affect the common circuit's work.

114
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:18,040
You see that reducing the pulse duration, the edge stays the same.

115
00:12:23,030 --> 00:12:25,970
And you can measure it in time.

116
00:12:29,300 --> 00:12:53,060
With this chain in the gate circuit — 4.7 Ω and a 4.7 Ω resistor — the signal rise edge on the FET gate is 300 ns.

117
00:12:53,060 --> 00:13:05,180
And the edge it's driven by is very steep — coming directly from the PWM controller.

118
00:13:05,640 --> 00:13:08,180
We care about precisely this parameter.

119
00:13:08,560 --> 00:13:13,420
And we can also look at the rear edge of switch closure.

120
00:13:17,290 --> 00:13:21,050
This edge is about 200 ns.

121
00:13:23,530 --> 00:13:34,490
Now about the moment I was talking about — picking that unspecified resistor.

122
00:13:34,490 --> 00:13:47,110
If we short it — I'll do this now with tweezers — you can see the edge will grow.

123
00:13:48,310 --> 00:13:50,850
Steepness of the opening edge.

124
00:13:54,970 --> 00:14:08,850
You see that when shorted, the opening edge steepness increases.

125
00:14:09,730 --> 00:14:14,190
From 300 ns to 200 ns.

126
00:14:15,190 --> 00:14:29,490
Which means we have a wide range for picking these gate-circuit resistors to set clear power switch operation.

127
00:14:30,070 --> 00:14:33,950
That ends the operation check.

128
00:14:34,330 --> 00:14:36,570
The circuits are finished, all functioning.

129
00:14:37,090 --> 00:14:41,290
The same checks should be done on each optical driver.

130
00:14:41,390 --> 00:14:43,510
The picture should be maintained.

131
00:14:43,510 --> 00:14:46,790
So we do the first system startup.

132
00:14:47,470 --> 00:14:51,730
I always recommend doing this using an incandescent lamp.

133
00:14:52,290 --> 00:15:03,850
Carefully check once more the whole supply wire schematic — the polarity brought to the connection of the electrolytic capacitors.

134
00:15:04,010 --> 00:15:08,670
Because reversing it can lead to failure.

135
00:15:09,410 --> 00:15:16,670
And without applying power to the scheme, first check the power module.

136
00:15:17,010 --> 00:15:19,910
For this connect one of the wires to the battery.

137
00:15:19,930 --> 00:15:23,130
In this case I connected the minus of the power source.

138
00:15:23,970 --> 00:15:37,930
And the plus lead, going to the cap bank and then to the power switches, I connect through an incandescent lamp.

139
00:15:37,930 --> 00:15:43,770
It'll immediately show if there's a malfunction.

140
00:15:44,390 --> 00:15:45,910
Watch — I connect.

141
00:15:47,590 --> 00:15:51,050
And you can see the lamp briefly flashed.

142
00:15:51,310 --> 00:15:57,570
And further its connection doesn't lead to filament glow.

143
00:15:58,410 --> 00:16:04,250
The first flash signified that the caps got charged.

144
00:16:04,250 --> 00:16:16,450
And the moment that the lamp doesn't light testifies that the power block is correctly assembled and the switches don't pass current without control.

145
00:16:17,690 --> 00:16:25,170
Now after we've confirmed this, we can move to testing the block.

146
00:16:26,390 --> 00:16:30,530
Confirm the system is off.

147
00:16:30,770 --> 00:16:37,790
Using the resistor slider, set it to non-working mode.

148
00:16:38,630 --> 00:16:44,690
Extreme position — smallest pulse duration, or rather their full absence.

149
00:16:45,390 --> 00:16:49,250
And now connect the system.

150
00:16:50,470 --> 00:16:54,310
For this purpose you can use an ammeter.

151
00:16:55,070 --> 00:17:02,330
Very useful — with it you can observe the current the system draws.

152
00:17:03,110 --> 00:17:07,510
Connect the battery.

153
00:17:07,710 --> 00:17:12,290
And now we can apply power to the DC-DC converter.

154
00:17:14,130 --> 00:17:15,810
Power supplied.

155
00:17:16,810 --> 00:17:25,150
Let me say right away that the turn count in the pulse transformer is pretty high.

156
00:17:25,290 --> 00:17:29,570
Transformation ratio is high at steep pulses.

157
00:17:29,770 --> 00:17:33,250
And the voltage here will be pretty high.

158
00:17:33,250 --> 00:17:46,870
You can see that the system isn't running and there's no discharge at the outputs.

159
00:17:46,990 --> 00:17:52,650
Now I shorted the green start wire and the end of the transformer winding.

160
00:17:53,310 --> 00:17:57,850
Now I slightly add pulse duration.

161
00:18:00,890 --> 00:18:06,330
And you see a small discharge appeared.

162
00:18:07,590 --> 00:18:13,530
The system started — you can also control by ammeter.

163
00:18:13,850 --> 00:18:15,710
Consumption is very small now.

164
00:18:16,790 --> 00:18:17,850
Add more.

165
00:18:20,530 --> 00:18:21,570
Watch.

166
00:18:24,130 --> 00:18:27,170
The discharge already increased its length.

167
00:18:28,170 --> 00:18:30,850
And already stretches.

168
00:18:31,870 --> 00:18:34,870
The system works.

169
00:18:35,770 --> 00:18:43,510
In this visual way we can tell how the voltage rises.

170
00:18:47,750 --> 00:18:49,470
Add more.

171
00:18:56,750 --> 00:19:04,730
I'll tell you guys, this is well over 1000 V with a discharge like this.

172
00:19:04,850 --> 00:19:09,050
At touching, the wires stick together.

173
00:19:10,930 --> 00:19:16,790
Wish I could get the ammeter in the lens.

174
00:19:17,890 --> 00:19:19,790
Try to do this now.

175
00:19:21,450 --> 00:19:22,530
So.

176
00:19:23,670 --> 00:19:25,750
So it's visible.

177
00:19:25,910 --> 00:19:26,790
Needle at zero.

178
00:19:42,050 --> 00:19:43,750
Bad contact a bit.

179
00:19:43,830 --> 00:19:44,910
Here it is now.

180
00:19:49,010 --> 00:19:58,370
We see that under shorting, consumption reaches 9 A.

181
00:19:59,530 --> 00:20:02,350
Add more pulse duration.

182
00:20:09,790 --> 00:20:12,470
10 A short.

183
00:20:14,130 --> 00:20:16,850
Add full duration now.

184
00:20:18,750 --> 00:20:22,370
Probably we'll get a specific discharge.

185
00:20:24,770 --> 00:20:29,770
With this matter you have to be more careful.

186
00:20:32,970 --> 00:20:42,110
Such experiments are better conducted through a lamp bulb so the system doesn't fail.

187
00:20:46,210 --> 00:20:48,430
You see it all yourselves.

188
00:20:50,950 --> 00:20:54,290
Hellish power in this system.

189
00:21:02,100 --> 00:21:05,440
Switch to off mode.

190
00:21:07,400 --> 00:21:13,160
Now we're interested in tuning this system by frequency.

191
00:21:13,280 --> 00:21:15,500
For this we need an oscilloscope.

192
00:21:16,280 --> 00:21:23,920
Look at the oscillogram on one of the transformer taps relative to the starting tap.

193
00:21:24,140 --> 00:21:27,300
And tune to the optimal frequency.

194
00:21:27,300 --> 00:21:30,900
Tune the core to the operating frequency.

195
00:21:32,260 --> 00:21:37,300
For this I connected the yellow oscilloscope channel to one of the taps.

196
00:21:37,380 --> 00:21:41,980
Specifically the third tap of the transformer, since the voltage here is high.

197
00:21:43,720 --> 00:21:47,320
If you count from the start of the winding.

198
00:21:48,560 --> 00:21:52,460
My probes are rated 1500 V, 100x suppression.

199
00:21:52,620 --> 00:21:54,960
So I'm not afraid for the device.

200
00:21:54,960 --> 00:22:04,380
If you have 10x suppression probes, it's better to do this on the first tap.

201
00:22:05,500 --> 00:22:10,000
Now power is supplied to the switches from the battery.

202
00:22:10,180 --> 00:22:14,420
And now I apply power to the DC-DC converter.

203
00:22:15,420 --> 00:22:25,240
With the resistor slider responsible for pulse duration switched to system off.

204
00:22:26,320 --> 00:22:30,480
Applying power to the converter.

205
00:22:30,840 --> 00:22:36,180
And we see for now there's nothing at the transformer output.

206
00:22:36,340 --> 00:22:41,860
Now I smoothly add the duration of control pulses.

207
00:22:45,230 --> 00:22:47,870
And you see this picture.

208
00:22:47,990 --> 00:22:55,850
With increasing duration you can see the number of these waves also increases.

209
00:22:56,330 --> 00:23:02,850
That means our core isn't in optimal operating mode.

210
00:23:03,250 --> 00:23:06,170
Pulse duration to full.

211
00:23:06,790 --> 00:23:11,430
And we can count the number of these waves.

212
00:23:11,430 --> 00:23:13,690
1, 2, 3, 4, 5.

213
00:23:14,310 --> 00:23:18,830
That is — we need to raise the frequency 5 times.

214
00:23:19,690 --> 00:23:21,510
For this transformer.

215
00:23:23,270 --> 00:23:24,930
We'll do this now.

216
00:23:29,260 --> 00:23:36,100
This resistor in the schematic is responsible for the frequency.

217
00:23:36,360 --> 00:23:41,180
At the values shown in the schematic.

218
00:23:42,180 --> 00:23:49,660
A 10 kΩ on pin 5 and 2200 pF on pin 7.

219
00:23:50,940 --> 00:23:57,300
The frequency can be regulated from 35 kHz to 185 kHz.

220
00:23:58,240 --> 00:23:59,700
On this PWM controller.

221
00:24:00,100 --> 00:24:02,880
And raising the frequency.

222
00:24:03,160 --> 00:24:09,540
Watch how the ringing phenomenon in the transformer disappears.

223
00:24:12,320 --> 00:24:16,040
This is a preliminary tuning.

224
00:24:16,920 --> 00:24:20,140
Next, after connecting the diode bridge.

225
00:24:21,200 --> 00:24:25,640
We'll correct the transformer operation.

226
00:24:25,720 --> 00:24:29,720
Directly under DC load.

227
00:24:30,720 --> 00:24:34,680
Now we'll remove this negative phenomenon.

228
00:24:36,780 --> 00:24:38,080
Of oscillations.

229
00:24:38,480 --> 00:24:39,660
Raise frequency.

230
00:24:39,660 --> 00:24:50,660
We need one pulse each.

231
00:24:51,920 --> 00:24:54,560
The power supply is grumbling a bit.

232
00:24:55,840 --> 00:25:00,980
Since it can't handle the DC-DC converter's consumption.

233
00:25:01,160 --> 00:25:01,660
But no matter.

234
00:25:03,880 --> 00:25:05,760
So we bring it.

235
00:25:11,010 --> 00:25:16,810
And here, practically what we need.

236
00:25:18,710 --> 00:25:23,590
Now we can control pulse duration.

237
00:25:25,350 --> 00:25:28,230
From zero to maximum.

238
00:25:30,970 --> 00:25:35,150
The oscillogram became significantly nicer.

239
00:25:36,150 --> 00:25:41,670
Now we need to connect a load at these points.

240
00:25:42,170 --> 00:25:44,910
And look at the signal shape under load.

241
00:25:44,990 --> 00:25:51,190
I connected a 60 W, 220 V lamp.

242
00:25:52,390 --> 00:25:57,030
And we'll observe the oscillogram and voltage on it.

243
00:25:58,550 --> 00:26:00,790
In parallel with its output.

244
00:26:00,790 --> 00:26:02,090
Apply power.

245
00:26:03,990 --> 00:26:08,290
And smoothly add the duration of control pulses.

246
00:26:13,800 --> 00:26:17,000
You see the lamp filament starts to glow.

247
00:26:18,660 --> 00:26:19,520
Go further.

248
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:27,360
Oscillogram changes.

249
00:26:27,840 --> 00:26:35,580
And here's the maximum duration of control pulses.

250
00:26:36,580 --> 00:26:38,660
This kind of oscillogram.

251
00:26:40,520 --> 00:26:42,980
You need to look at its symmetry.

252
00:26:43,140 --> 00:26:45,680
You see symmetric operation.

253
00:26:47,900 --> 00:26:52,460
Smooth regulation if we rotate the slider.

254
00:26:54,300 --> 00:26:56,080
Output voltage.

255
00:26:57,520 --> 00:27:05,800
At this stage we can consider preliminary system tuning finished.

256
00:27:06,980 --> 00:27:13,420
Frequency for us came out to about 93 kHz.

257
00:27:17,540 --> 00:27:20,020
Can add slightly more.

258
00:27:23,140 --> 00:27:27,380
But we'll do that after playing with frequency to the end.

259
00:27:27,380 --> 00:27:41,460
When we're looking at DC voltage here, we'll care about the maximum voltage rating on load at minimum consumption from the power source.

260
00:27:41,600 --> 00:27:44,160
That is, we'll need to watch the ammeter.

261
00:27:45,140 --> 00:27:50,440
At this stage we've confirmed the system is fully workable.

262
00:27:51,420 --> 00:27:54,520
Interesting — does it heat after this...

263
00:27:54,520 --> 00:27:56,400
Heat sink is absolutely cold.

264
00:27:58,060 --> 00:28:01,140
Cooling won't be needed at all.

265
00:28:02,780 --> 00:28:08,000
On that note, we'll say goodbye for the next episode.

266
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:15,300
All the best to everyone — and successful experiments.
